  "title": "Prehistoric Religion and Primitive Religion",
  "outline": [
    {
      "level": "A",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Prehistoric religion",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The study of prehistoric religion: nature, scope, methods of interpretation, problems special to the subject [see also 10/41. B.]",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Inferred prehistoric religious beliefs and practices",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Burial customs and cults of the dead",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Cannibalism",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Sacrifices: human, animal, and other offerings",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Hunting rites and animal cults",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Female fertility deities",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "f",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Shamanism, sorcery, and magic",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Religions attributed to various prehistoric cultural stages and regions",
          "children": []
        }
      ]
    },
    {
      "level": "B",
      "levelType": "major",
      "text": "Primitive religion",
      "children": [
        {
          "level": "1",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The nature and significance of primitive religion",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "2",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Primitive views of reality",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The distinction between the sacred and the profane",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Dynamistic, daemonistic, and theistic views of the sacred: the concept of mana",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Animism: external reality viewed as living presence",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Sacred time and times, sacred space and places, and man's nature, origin, and destiny: primitive cosmogonies, cosmologies, eschatologies",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "3",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The nature and function of myth and symbol in primitive religion: their role in ritual, the iconographic character of primitive art",
          "children": []
        },
        {
          "level": "4",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "Primitive religious practices and institutions",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Sacrifice, purification, passage rites",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Worship or veneration centred on natural objects or forces",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Totemism: the socio religious system in which men are intimately related to plants, animals, or other natural phenomena",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Worship of ancestors, kings, and heroes",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "e",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The roles of asceticism, shamanism, divination, and spiritualistic practices",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        },
        {
          "level": "5",
          "levelType": "numeric",
          "text": "The primitive religions of the major world areas",
          "children": [
            {
              "level": "a",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Africa: traditional religions of the indigenous African peoples",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "b",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Australia and Oceania: religions of the Pacific Island peoples",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "c",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "The Americas: religions of the indigenous peoples of North, Central, and South America [see also 822. 1.]",
              "children": []
            },
            {
              "level": "d",
              "levelType": "lowercase",
              "text": "Asia: aboriginal religions of Asian peoples",
              "children": []
            }
          ]
        }
      ]
    }
  ],
